// 1-2 digit substrate parser — the "easy start" of the arbitrary-
// precision (calc) thread per queue.md FV next-concrete-work #2.
//
// What this is. Given a String "47", compute the int 47 entirely
// through substrate operations. Two digits is enough to demonstrate
// the digit-extraction shape without yet needing the carry loop.
//
// Mechanism. Each digit character is its codepoint (ASCII '0' = 48,
// '9' = 57). Subtract 48 to recover the digit's integer value. Then
// 10 * d0 + d1 for a two-digit number. All operations are substrate-
// pure: `string_char_at` is a tensor index-select + saturating mask
// (see codegen_pytorch.string_char_at), the subtraction and the
// multiplication are number-axis tensor ops, and the sum is a
// vector add.
//
// What this is NOT. This is not arbitrary precision. The carry loop
// — what makes BigInt-style arithmetic possible — is the hard piece
// that comes next and likely needs a Sutra-side primitive (the queue
// flags this honestly). See planning/findings/2026-05-27-arbitrary-
// precision-parser.md for the analysis of what's blocked.
//
// 2026-05-27.

function int parse_int1(Character c) {
    // Single digit: codepoint - 48. Works for '0'..'9' only;
    // out-of-range input returns whatever (codepoint - 48) gives —
    // no validation, per Sutra's "no runtime errors by mechanism"
    // design. The validator is the last line of defense.
    return c.string_char_at(0) - 48;
}

function int parse_int2(String s) {
    // Two digits, big-endian: "47" -> 10*4 + 7 = 47.
    int d0 = s.string_char_at(0) - 48;
    int d1 = s.string_char_at(1) - 48;
    return 10 * d0 + d1;
}

function int main() {
    String s = String.make_string("47");
    return parse_int2(s);
}
